04344nam a22005535i 9780773562561DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735625617 a10.1515/97807735625612doi  a(DE-B1597)655970  a(OCoLC)732600713  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPQ3912bP87 1990eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a843/.5097141 aPurdy, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCertain Difficulty of Being :bEssays on the Quebec Novel /cAnthony Purdy. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- t"This is Not a Novel" The Rhetoric of Denial in Nineteenth-Century Quebec Novel Prefaces -- tBetween Epic and Novel: The Crisis of Community in Felix-Antoine Savard's Menaud, maitre-draveur -- tOn the Outside Looking In: The Political Economy of Everyday Life in Gabriette Roy's Bonheur d'occasion -- tStopping the Kaleidoscope: Narrative Ambiguity in André Langevin's Poussière sur la ville -- tThe Politics of Incoherence: Narrative Failure and the Invention of History in Hubert Aquin's Prochain épisode -- tAn Archaeology of the Self: Narrative Ventriloquism in Anne Hébert's Kamouraska -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Preface to A Certain Difficulty of Being Purdy examines the kinds of discourse that deal with the novel in some nineteenth-century Quebec novel prefaces, thereby revealing a theme of generic denegation in the sense of "This is not a novel." Purdy goes on to explore the transition from epic to novel in Félix-Antoine Savard's Menaud, maître-draveur; the contradictions stemming from the use of a first-person, present-tense narrative in André Langevin's Poussière sur la ville; the problem of narrativity and history as it is raised in Hubert Aquin's Prochain épisode; and the way in which narrative voice functions in Anne Hébert's Kamouraska. He also touches on the current debate concerning the boundaries between modernism and post-modernism. Purdy does not offer an all-embracing system to explain the development of narrative in the Quebec novel, but leads us to an understanding of how these particular novels function, each in its own socio-historical context, and how they achieve or fail to achieve what they set out to do. The thread that runs through the different chapters is a pragmatic concern with Quebec's historical "difficulty of being" as it informs in varying ways the narrative projects of the novels in question.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench-Canadian fictionxHistory and criticismxQuébec (Province). 0aFrench-Canadian fictionzQuébec (Province)xHistory and criticism. 0aQuébec (Province) dans la littérature. 0aRoman québécoisxHistoire et critique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356256140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562561/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles